Introduction¶

The dataset I was working on is the 'Loan Data from Prosper' dataset. It is a relatively large datsaet with alot of variables. It contains loans data from the year 2005 up until 2014. For my approach only a few of the aforementioned variables will be explored. The purpose of this analysis is to investigate the yearly trends in loans borrowed, factors affecting the BorrowerRates and borrowing trends among various categories (eg. Homeownership, Employment status etc.) My study will seek to answer questions like:

How does the distribution of Loan Interest rates look like? How do different employment statuses rank ? How is the distribution of loan amounts(LoanOriginalAmount) borrowed? What are the yearly trends of loan amounts borrowed What categories of people are seen to borrow the most loans? What is the distribution of loan Investors?

For this analysis I will focus mostly on the following variables LoanOriginalAmount,Investors,BorrowerRate,BorrowerAPR,LoanOriginationQuarter, StatedMonthlyIncome,IsBorrowerHomeowner,EmploymentStatus,InvestmentFromFriendsAmount I will require to engineer new meaningful features too like YearBorrowed

#Change the variables 'prosperRating' into Categorical variables 
ratings = ['HR','E','D','C','B','A','AA']
years = CategoricalDtype(['2005','2006','2007','2008','2009','2010','2011','2012','2013','2014'], ordered = True)
prospRt = CategoricalDtype(ratings, ordered = True)
ln_status = CategoricalDtype(['Current','Completed','FinalPaymentProgress',r'PastDue(1-15 days)',r'PastDue(16-30 days)',
                              r'PastDue(31-60 days)',r'PastDue(61-90 days)',r'PastDue(91-120 days)',r'PastDue(>120 days)',
                              'Chargedoff','Defaulted','Cancelled'], ordered = True)

loans_sub[r'ProsperRating (Alpha)'] = loans_sub[r'ProsperRating (Alpha)'].astype(prospRt)
loans_sub['YearBorrowed'] = loans_sub['YearBorrowed'].astype(years)
loans_sub['LoanStatus'] = loans_sub['LoanStatus'].astype(ln_status)

#histogram function
def histplt(df, x, bin_vals,log):
    if (log == True):
        bins = 10 ** np.arange(bin_vals[0],bin_vals[1] + bin_vals[2], bin_vals[2])
        plt.xscale('log')
    else:
        bins = np.arange(bin_vals[0],bin_vals[1] + bin_vals[2], bin_vals[2])        
    plt.hist(data = df, x = x, bins = bins)
    plt.xlabel(x)
    plt.ylabel('Count');

histplt(loans_sub, 'StatedMonthlyIncome', [3.08,6.1,0.05], True)
ticks = [1000,3000,10000, 30000, 100000]
labels = ['{}'.format(v) for v in ticks]
plt.xticks(ticks, labels, rotation = 50);

From the plot above, the distribution of StatedMonthlyIncome is unimodal, with alot of the values falling at around 5000

I was required to log transform the x axis because the initial plot without transformation appeared to have a long tail.

numeric_vars = ['BorrowerAPR','BorrowerRate','StatedMonthlyIncome','LoanOriginalAmount', 'InvestmentFromFriendsAmount', 'Investors']
loans_samp = loans_sub.sample(n = 300, replace = False)

g = sb.PairGrid(data = loans_sub, vars = numeric_vars)
g = g.map_diag(plt.hist, bins = 20,)
g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter, alpha = 1/20);

As expected, The variables BorrowerRate and BorrowerAPR are highly correlated Investors seems to be directly proportional to the LoanOriginalAmount which is worth exploring. There doesnt seem to be much investment from friends judging from how straight its scatter plot is on both axes

Conclusions¶

You can write a summary of the main findings and reflect on the steps taken during the data exploration. The dataset provided was already wrangled so i did not have to do m,uch cleaning. I first extracted the columns that seemed to me as the most important ones to my study (about 27 variables). My finding were as follows:

There seems to be very little of 2005 data provided on the dataset closely followed by 2006 which has more data but ultimately quite little. Most of the loan amounts borrowed fall within the 4000 dollar mark. From the dataset, we can see that the majority of the loans are still current meaning that they are yet to be fully repaid but are still within the next payment window. The BorrowerRate and BorrowerAPR are very closely related as they represent somewhat similar ideas. Most of the values appear to attract a Borrowerrate and BorrowerAPR of 0.3 and 0.3-4 respectively.

Homeowners are seen to be the more frequent loaners compared to non homeowners. Employed folk also appear to be more likely to take up loans compared to non-employed folk. They year 2013 recorded the highest amounts of loans borrowed, with 2005 recording a nearly misleading least, pointing to the possibility of missing data. From the provided data, it does not seem like plenty of the loans received investment from friends. Investors distribution could be considered normal save for the fact that there is a large amount of loans having 1 investor.
